# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acidulidesulfobacteriota
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Acid rock drainage occurs naturally within some environments as part of the rock weathering process but is exacerbated by large-scale earth disturbances characteristic of mining and other large construction activities, usually within rocks containing an abundance of sulfide minerals.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Areas where the earth has been disturbed (e.g. construction sites or highway construction) may create acid rock drainage.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In many localities, the liquid that drains from coal stocks, coal handling facilities, coal washeries, and coal waste tips can be highly acidic, and in such cases it is treated as acid rock drainage.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] These, combined with reduced pH, have a detrimental impact on the streams' aquatic environments.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The same type of chemical reactions and processes may occur through the disturbance of acid sulfate soils formed under coastal or estuarine conditions after the last major sea level rise, and constitutes a similar environmental hazard.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Historically, the acidic discharges from active or abandoned mines were called acid mine drainage, or AMD.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The term acid rock drainage, or ARD, was introduced in the 1980s and 1990s to indicate that acidic drainage can originate from sources other than mines.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] For example, a paper presented in 1991 at a major international conference on this subject was titled: "The Prediction of Acid Rock Drainage – Lessons from the Database".
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Both AMD and ARD refer to low pH or acidic waters caused by the oxidation of sulfide minerals, though ARD is the more generic name.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In cases where drainage from a mine is not acidic and has dissolved metals or metalloids, or was originally acidic, but has been neutralized along its flow path, then it is described as "neutral mine drainage", "mining-influenced water" or otherwise.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] None of these other names have gained general acceptance.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Sub-surface mining often progresses below the water table, so water must be constantly pumped out of the mine in order to prevent flooding.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] When a mine is abandoned, the pumping ceases, and water floods the mine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] This introduction of water is the initial step in most acid rock drainage situations.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Tailings piles or ponds, mine waste rock dumps, and coal spoils are also an important source of acid mine drainage.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] After being exposed to air and water, oxidation of metal sulfides (often pyrite, which is iron-sulfide) within the surrounding rock and overburden generates acidity.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Colonies of bacteria and archaea greatly accelerate the decomposition of metal ions, although the reactions also occur in an abiotic environment.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] These microbes, called extremophiles for their ability to survive in harsh conditions, occur naturally in the rock, but limited water and oxygen supplies usually keep their numbers low.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Extremophiles known as acidophiles especially favor the low pH levels of abandoned mines.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In particular, *Acidithiobacillus ferrooxidans* is a key contributor to pyrite oxidation.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Metal mines may generate highly acidic discharges where the ore is a sulfide mineral or is associated with pyrite.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In these cases the predominant metal ion may not be iron but rather zinc, copper, or nickel.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The most commonly mined ore of copper, chalcopyrite, is itself a copper-iron-sulfide and occurs with a range of other sulfides.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Thus, copper mines are often major culprits of acid mine drainage.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] At some mines, acidic drainage is detected within 2–5 years after mining begins, whereas at other mines, it is not detected for several decades.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In addition, acidic drainage may be generated for decades or centuries after it is first detected.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] For this reason, acid mine drainage is considered a serious long-term environmental problem associated with mining.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The chemistry of oxidation of pyrites, the production of ferrous ions and subsequently ferric ions, is very complex, and this complexity has considerably inhibited the design of effective treatment options.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Although a host of chemical processes contribute to acid mine drainage, pyrite oxidation is by far the greatest contributor.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Either of these reactions can occur spontaneously or can be catalyzed by microorganisms that derive energy from the oxidation reaction.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The net effect of these reactions is to release H+, which lowers the pH and maintains the solubility of the ferric ion.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Water temperatures as high as 47 °C (117 °F) have been measured underground at the Iron Mountain Mine, and the pH can be as low as −3.6.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Organisms which cause acid mine drainage can thrive in waters with pH very close to zero.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Negative pH occurs when water evaporates from already acidic pools thereby increasing the concentration of hydrogen ions.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] About half of the coal mine discharges in Pennsylvania have pH under 5.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] However, a portion of mine drainage in both the bituminous and anthracite regions of Pennsylvania is alkaline, because limestone in the overburden neutralizes acid before the drainage emanates.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] When the pH of acid mine drainage is raised past 3, either through contact with fresh water or neutralizing minerals, previously soluble iron(III) ions precipitate as iron(III) hydroxide, a yellow-orange solid colloquially known as *yellow boy*.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Other types of iron precipitates are possible, including iron oxides and oxyhydroxides, and sulfates such as jarosite.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] All these precipitates can discolor water and smother plant and animal life on the streambed, disrupting stream ecosystems (a specific offense under the Fisheries Act in Canada).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The process also produces additional hydrogen ions, which can further decrease pH.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In some cases, the concentrations of iron hydroxides in yellow boy are so high the precipitate can be recovered for commercial use in pigments.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Many acid rock discharges also contain elevated levels of potentially toxic metals, especially nickel and copper with lower levels of a range of trace and semi-metal ions such as lead, arsenic, aluminium, and manganese.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The elevated levels of heavy metals can only be dissolved in waters that have a low pH, as is found in the acidic waters produced by pyrite oxidation.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In the coal belt around the south Wales valleys in the UK highly acidic nickel-rich discharges from coal stocking sites have proved to be particularly troublesome.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Acid mine drainage also affects the wildlife living within the affected body of water.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Aquatic macroinvertebrates living in streams or parts of streams affected by acid mine drainage show fewer individuals, less diversity, and lower biomass.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Many species of fish also cannot tolerate the pollution.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Among the macroinvertebrates, certain species can be found at only certain levels of pollution, while other species can be found over a wide range.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In a mining setting it is leading practice to carry out a geochemical assessment of mine materials during the early stages of a project to determine the potential for AMD.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The geochemical assessment aims to map the distribution and variability of key geochemical parameters, acid generating and element leaching characteristics.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In the United Kingdom, many discharges from abandoned mines are exempt from regulatory control.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Although abandoned underground mines produce most of the acid mine drainage, some recently mined and reclaimed surface mines have produced ARD and have degraded local groundwater and surface-water resources.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Acidic water produced at active mines must be neutralized to achieve pH 6–9 before discharge from a mine site to a stream is permitted.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In Canada, work to reduce the effects of acid mine drainage is concentrated under the Mine Environment Neutral Drainage (MEND) program.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Total liability from acid rock drainage is estimated to be between CA$2 billion and CA$5 billion.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Over a period of eight years, MEND claims to have reduced ARD liability by up to CA$400 million, from an investment of CA$17.5 million.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In such cases, crushed limestone can be dumped on site as a neutralizing agent.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] However, although limestone is an unprocessed raw material available in large quantities and the least expensive neutralization agent, it can suffer from a number of disadvantages possibly limiting its applications.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Indeed, small calcium carbonate grains of crushed limestone can be prone to the formation of a coating of gypsum (CaSO4·2H2O) surrounded by a thin impermeable and protective film of less soluble Fe-Al hydroxysulfate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] This coating is sometimes referred to in the literature as an *armor* (shield, encrustation, rim, rind...).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] When present, it passivates the limestone surface, preventing calcite dissolution and the further release of bicarbonate in solution.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] This might explain why at Cwm Rheidol in mid Wales, the positive impact of limestone application has been much less than anticipated because of the formation of a poorly soluble calcium sulfate layer onto the surface of limestone chips, binding the material and preventing further neutralization.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Depending on the volume and flowrate of acid effluents to be neutralised and the scale of industrial installations, a common but more expensive commercial process for treating acid mine drainage is precipitation with lime in a high-density sludge (HDS) process.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In this application, a slurry of lime (CaO – Ca(OH)2 after hydration) is dispersed into a tank containing acid mine drainage and recycled sludge to increase water pH to about 9.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] At this pH, most toxic metals become insoluble and precipitate, aided by the presence of recycled sludge.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Optionally, air can be injected in the tank to oxidize iron(II) and manganese(II) and assist in their precipitation.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The resulting slurry is directed to a sludge-settling vessel, such as a clarifier.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In that vessel, clean water will overflow for release, whereas settled metal precipitates (sludge) are recycled to the acid mine drainage treatment tank, with a sludge-wasting side stream.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] A number of variations of this process exist, as dictated by the chemistry of ARD, its volume, and other factors.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Generally, the products of the HDS process also contain gypsum (CaSO4) and unreacted lime, which enhance both its settleability and resistance to re-acidification and metal mobilization.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Less complex variants of this process, such as simple lime neutralization, may involve no more than a lime silo, a mixing tank and a settling pond.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] These systems are far less costly to build, but are also less efficient (longer reaction times are required, and they produce a discharge with higher trace metal concentrations, if present).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] They would be suitable for relatively small flows or less complex acid mine drainage.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] A calcium silicate feedstock, made from processed steel slag, can also be used to neutralize active acidity in AMD systems by removing free hydrogen ions from the bulk solution, thereby increasing pH.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] As the silicate anion captures H+ ions (raising the pH), it forms monosilicic acid (H4SiO4), a neutral solute.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Monosilicic acid remains in the bulk solution and play many roles in correcting the adverse effects of acidic conditions.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In the bulk solution, the silicate anion is very effective in neutralizing H+ cations in the soil solution.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] While its mode-of-action is quite different from limestone, the ability of calcium silicate to neutralize acid solutions is equivalent to limestone as evidenced by its CCE value of 90–100% and its relative neutralizing value of 98%.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In the presence of heavy metals, calcium silicate reacts in a different way than limestone.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] As limestone raises the pH of the bulk solution, when heavy metals are present, precipitation of the poorly soluble metal hydroxides is accelerated and the tendency for an impermeable metal hydroxide coating, termed *armoring*, to form on limestone grains surface increases significantly.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Limestone grains become coated by a rind of gypsum encapsulated itself in a thin external film of impermeable and protective Fe-Al hydroxysulfate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] *Armoring* slows the CaCO3 dissolution and prevents the limestone grains from releasing additional alkalinity in solution.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In the calcium silicate aggregates, as silicic acid species are adsorbed onto the metal hydroxide surface, the development of silica layers (mono- and bi-layers) lead to the formation of colloidal complexes with neutral or negative surface charges.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] These negatively charged colloids are electrostatically repelled by each other (as well as with the negatively charged calcium silicate granules).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Cation exchange processes have previously been investigated as a potential treatment for acid mine drainage.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The principle is that an ion-exchange resin can remove potentially toxic metals (cationic resins), or chlorides, sulfates and uranyl sulfate complexes (anionic resins) from mine water.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Once the contaminants are adsorbed, the exchange sites on resins must be regenerated, which typically requires acidic and basic reagents and generates a brine that contains the pollutants in a concentrated form.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] A South African company that won the 2013 IChemE award for water management and supply (treating AMD) has developed a patented ion-exchange process that treats mine effluents (and AMD) economically.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Constructed wetlands systems have been proposed during the 1980s to treat acid mine drainage generated by the abandoned coal mines in Eastern Appalachia.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Generally, the wetlands receive near-neutral water, after it has been typically neutralized by a limestone-based treatment process.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Metal precipitation occurs from their oxidation at near-neutral pH, complexation with organic matter, precipitation as carbonates or sulfides.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The latter results from sediment-borne anaerobic bacteria capable of reducing sulfate ions into sulfide ions.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] These sulfide ions can then bind with heavy metal ions, precipitating heavy metals out of solution and effectively reversing the entire process.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The attractiveness of a constructed wetlands solution lies in its relative low cost.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Typically, the effluent from constructed wetland receiving near-neutral water will be well-buffered at 6.5–7.0 and can readily be discharged.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Some of the metal precipitates retained in sediments are easily oxidised and remobilised when exposed to atmospheric oxygen (e.g., copper sulfide or elemental selenium), and it is very important that the wetland sediments remain largely and permanently submerged to keep them insoluble and immobile.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Prolonged droughts caused by climate warming might compromise the proper functioning and the safety of some constructed wetlands if during an extremely hot summer water supply decreases and evaporation accelerates causing them to dry up.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] An example of an effective constructed wetland is on the Afon Pelena in the River Afan valley above Port Talbot where highly ferruginous discharges from the Whitworth mine have been successfully treated.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Most base metals in acidic solution precipitate in contact with free sulfide, e.g. from H2S or NaHS.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Solid-liquid separation after reaction would produce a base metal-free effluent that can be discharged or further treated to reduce sulfate, and a metal sulfide concentrate with possible economic value.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] As an alternative, several researchers have investigated the precipitation of metals using biogenic sulfide.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] In this process, sulfate-reducing bacteria (SRB) oxidize organic matter using sulfate as terminal electron acceptor, instead of oxygen.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Their metabolic products include bicarbonate produced by organic matter oxidation, which can neutralize water acidity, and hydrogen sulfide, which forms highly insoluble precipitates with many toxic metals.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Although promising, this process has been slow in being adopted for a variety of technical reasons.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Many technologies exist for the treatment of AMD.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] With the advance of large-scale sequencing strategies, genomes of microorganisms in the acid mine drainage community are directly sequenced from the environment.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] The nearly full genomic constructs allows new understanding of the community and able to reconstruct their metabolic pathways.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Our knowledge of acidophiles in acid mine drainage remains rudimentary: we know of many more species associated with ARD than we can establish roles and functions.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Scientists have recently begun to explore acid mine drainage and mine reclamation sites for unique soil bacteria capable of producing new pharmaceutical leads.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] Soil microbes have long been a source for effective drugs and new research, such as that conducted at the Center for Pharmaceutical Research and Innovation, suggests these extreme environments to be an untapped source for new discovery.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] This list includes both mines producing acid mine drainage and river systems significantly affected by such drainage.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acid-mine-drainage] It is by no means complete, as worldwide, several thousands of such sites exist.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] The outflow of acidic liquids and other pollutants from mines is often catalysed by acid-loving microorganisms; these are the **acidophiles in acid mine drainage**.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Acidophiles are not just present in exotic environments such as Yellowstone National Park or deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Genera such as *Acidithiobacillus* and *Leptospirillum* bacteria, and *Thermoplasmatales archaea*, are present in syntrophic relationships in the more mundane environments of concrete sewer pipes and implicated in the heavy-metal-containing, sulfurous waters of rivers such as the Rheidol.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Such microorganisms are responsible for the phenomenon of acid mine drainage (AMD) and thus are important both economically and from a conservation perspective.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Control of these acidophiles and their harnessing for industrial biotechnology shows their effect need not be entirely negative.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] The use of acidophilic organisms in mining is a new technique for extracting trace metals through bioleaching, and offers solutions for acid mine drainage in mining spoils.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Upon exposure to oxygen (O2) and water (H2O), metal sulfides undergo oxidation to produce metal-rich acidic effluent.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] If the pH is low enough to overcome the natural buffering capacity of the surrounding rocks (‘calcium carbonate equivalent’ or ‘acid neutralising capacity’), the surrounding area may become acidic, as well as contaminated with high levels of heavy metals.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Though acidophiles have an important place in the iron and sulfur biogeochemical cycles, strongly acidic environments are overwhelmingly anthropogenic in cause, primarily created at the cessation of mining operations where sulfide minerals, such as pyrite (iron disulfide or FeS2), are present.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Acid mine drainage may occur in the mine itself, the spoil heap (particularly colliery spoils from coal mining), or through some other activity that exposes metal sulfides at a high concentration, such as at major construction sites.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] The oxidation of metal sulfide (by oxygen) is slow without colonization by acidophiles, particularly *Acidithiobacillus ferrooxidans* (synonym *Thiobacillus ferrooxidans*).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] These bacteria can accelerate pyritic oxidation by 106 times.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Under the above acidic conditions, ferric iron (Fe3+) is a more potent oxidant than oxygen, resulting in faster pyrite oxidation rates.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] The process proceeds through *A.ferrooxidans* exhibiting a quorum level for the trigger of acid mine drainage (AMD).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] At first colonisation of metal sulfides there is no AMD, and as the bacteria grow into microcolonies, AMD remains absent, then at a certain colony size, the population begins to produce a measurable change in water chemistry, and AMD escalates.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] This means pH is not a clear measure of a mine's liability to AMD; culturing *A.ferrooxidans* (or others) gives a definite indication of a future AMD issue.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Other bacteria also implicated in AMD include *Leptospirillum ferrooxidans*, *Acidithiobacillus thiooxidans* and *Sulfobacillus thermosulfidooxidans*.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Though Pseudomonadota (formerly proteobacteria) display impressive acid tolerance, most retain a circumneutral cytoplasm to avoid denaturation of their acid-labile cell constituents.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Archaea such as *Ferroplasma acidiphilum*, which oxidises ferrous iron, have a number of intracellular enzymes with an optimum similar to that of their external acidic environment.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] This may explain their ability to survive pH as low as 1.3.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] The differing cell membranes in archaea compared to the bacteria may hold part of the explanation; ether lipids that link isoprene, compared to Pseudomonadota's di-ester linkage, are central to the difference.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Though lacking a cell wall, *F. acidiphilum* cell membranes contain caldarchaetidylglycerol tetraether lipids, which effectively block almost all proton access, *Thermoplasma acidophilum* also uses these bulky isoprenoid cores in its phospholipid bilayer.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] It is possible that the family Ferroplasmaceae may in fact be more important in AMD than the current paradigm, Acidithiobacillaceae.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] From a practical viewpoint this changes little, as despite the myriad physiological differences between archaea and bacteria, treatments would remain the same; if pH is kept high, and water and oxygen are prohibited from the pyrite, the reaction will be negligible.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] The isolation from solfataric soils of two Picrophilus species of archaea *P.oshimae* and *P.torridus* are of note for their record low of survival at pH 0, indicating that further AMD microorganisms may remain to be found which operate at an even lower pH.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Though the genus Picrophilus is not known to be involved in AMD, its extreme acidophily is of interest, for instance its proton-resistant liposomes, which could be present in AMD acidophiles.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Tentatively, there may be examples of syntrophy between acidophilic species, and even cross-domain cooperation between archaea and bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] One mutualistic example is the rotation of iron between species; ferrous-oxidising chemolithotrophs use iron as an electron donor, then ferric-reducing heterotrophs use iron as an electron-acceptor.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Another more synergistic behaviour is the faster oxidation of ferrous iron when *A.ferrooxidans* and *Sulfobacillus thermosulfidooxidans* are combined in low-CO2 culture.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] *S.thermosulfidooxidans* is a more efficient iron-oxidiser, but this is usually inhibited by low-CO2 uptake.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] *A.ferrooxidans* has a higher affinity for the gas, but a lower iron oxidation speed, and so can supply *S.thermosulfidooxidans* for mutual benefit.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Acidophiles display a great range of adaptations to not just tolerating, but thriving in an extreme pH environment (the definition of an acidophile being an organism that has a pH optimum below pH 3).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Principal in these is the necessity of maintaining a large pH gradient, to ensure a circumneutral cytoplasm (normally, however not in Picrophilus species).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] The archaeans have already been discussed above, and further information on their and bacterial adaptations are in basic form in the **Figure**.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] To elaborate upon the figure, the bacteria also use membrane proton blocking to maintain a high cytoplasmic pH, which is a passive system as even non-respiring *A.ferrooxidans* exhibit it.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] To grow at low pH, acidophiles must maintain a pH gradient of several pH units across the cellular membrane.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Acidophiles harness the strong proton motive force (PMF), caused by the pH gradient across their cell membrane, for ATP production.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] A large amount of energy is available to the acidophile through proton movement across the membrane, but with it comes cytoplasmic acidity.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Instead ions such as sodium can be used as a substitute energy transducer to avoid this pH increase (ATPases are often Na+ linked, rather than H+ linked).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Alternatively bacteria can use H+ containing vesicles to avoid cytoplasmic acidity (see **Figure**), but most require that any H+ taken in must be extruded after use in the electron transport chain (ETC).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] On the subject of the ETC, an adaptation to living in the mine environment is in the use of different ETC electron acceptors to neutralophiles; sulfur, arsenic, selenium, uranium, iron, and manganese in solid form rather than O2 (most commonly Fe in dissimilatory iron reduction, frequent in AMD).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Genomic adaptations are also present, but not without complications in organisms like Thermoplasmatales archaea, which is both acidophilic and thermophilic.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] For instance, this Order expresses an increased concentration of purine-containing codons for heat-stability, whilst increasing pyramidine codons in long open reading frames for protection from acid-stress.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] More generally, and presumably to reduce the chances of an acid-hydrolysis mutation, all obligate hyperacidophiles have truncated genomes when compared to neutralophile microorganisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] *Picrophilus torridus*, for instance, has the highest coding density of any non-parasitic aerobic microorganism living on organic substrates.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Acidophiles also benefit from improved DNA and protein repair systems such as chaperones involved in protein refolding.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] The *P.torridus* genome just mentioned contains a large numbers of genes concerned with repair proteins.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Bioremediation is the primary biotech issue created by the AMD acidophiles.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] A number of other neutralising agents are available (pulverised fuel ash-based grouts, cattle manure, whey, brewer's yeast) many which solve a waste disposal problem from another industry.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] As supplies of some metals dwindle, other methods of extraction are being explored, including the use of acidophiles, in a process known as bioleaching.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Though slower than conventional methods, the microorganisms (which can also include fungi) enable the exploitation of extremely low grade ores with minimum expense.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Projects include nickel extraction with *A.ferrooxidans* and *Aspergillus sp.* fungi and sulfur removal from coal with *Acidithiobacillus sp.*.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] The extraction can occur at the mine site, from waste water streams (or the main watercourse if the contamination has reached that far), in bioreactors, or at a power station (for instance to remove sulfur from coal before combustion to avoid sulfuric acid rain).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] AMD continues to be important in the River Rheidol, and in the near future further treatment will be needed in the area around Aberystwyth, which contains 38 of the 50 worst polluting metal mines in Wales.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] In 2007, the UK government endorsed a return to coal as an energy source and mining in the UK is increasing (for instance the open-cast coal pit at Ffos-y-fran, Merthyr Tydfil).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Much preventative work will be required to avoid the AMD associated with the last generation of coal mines.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] The fast and efficient protein and DNA repair systems show promise for human medical uses, particularly with regard to cancer and ageing.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] However further research is required to determine whether these systems really are qualitatively different, and how that can be applied from microorganisms to humans.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] As discussed above, acidophiles can have the option to use electron acceptors other than oxygen.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Johnson (1998) points out that facultative anaerobism of acidophiles, previously dismissed, could have major implications for AMD control.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidophiles-in-acid-mine-drainage] Further research is needed to determine how far current methods to block oxygen will working, in light of the fact that the reaction may be able to continue anaerobically.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Acidulidesulfobacteriota are ecologically significant in biogeochemical cycling, especially with respect to sulfur and iron.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Their genomes show evidence of interaction with viruses, which can influence host metabolic functions including folate biosynthesis and sulfur pathways.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Like all animals, humans carry vast numbers (approximately 1013 to 1014) of bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Most are in the gut, though there are many on the skin.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Most of the bacteria in and on the body are harmless or rendered so by the protective effects of the immune system, and many are beneficial, particularly the ones in the gut.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] However, several species of bacteria are pathogenic and cause infectious diseases, including cholera, syphilis, anthrax, leprosy, tuberculosis, tetanus and bubonic plague.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The most common fatal bacterial diseases are respiratory infections.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Antibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections and are also used in farming, making antibiotic resistance a growing problem.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Once regarded as plants constituting the class *Schizomycetes* ("fission fungi"), bacteria are now classified as prokaryotes.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Unlike cells of animals and other eukaryotes, bacterial cells contain circular chromosomes, do not contain a nucleus and rarely harbour membrane-bound organelles.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Although the term *bacteria* traditionally included all prokaryotes, the scientific classification changed after the discovery in the 1990s that prokaryotes consist of two very different groups of organisms that evolved from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] These evolutionary domains are called Bacteria and Archaea.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Unlike Archaea, bacteria contain ester-linked lipids in the cell membrane, possess elongation factors that are resistant to ADP-ribosylation by diphtheria toxin, use formylmethionine in protein synthesis initiation, and have numerous genetic differences, including a different 16S rRNA.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The word was first used to refer to bacteria in 1828.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Although an estimated 43,000 species of bacteria have been named, most of them have never been studied.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In fact, just 10 bacterial species account for half of all publications, whereas nearly 75% of all named bacteria have no academic research devoted to them.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The best-studied species, *Escherichia coli*, has more than 300,000 studies published on it, but many of these papers likely use it only as a cloning vehicle to study other species, without providing any insight into its own biology.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] 90% of scientific studies on bacteria focus on less than 1% of species, mostly pathogenic bacteria relevant to human health.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] While *E. coli* is probably the best-studied bacterium, a quarter of its 4000 genes are poorly studied or remain uncharacterized.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria with minimal genomes (< 600 genes, e.g.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] *Mycoplasma*) usually have a large fraction of their genes functionally characterized, given that most of them are essential and conserved in many other species.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The ancestors of bacteria were unicellular microorganisms that were the first forms of life to appear on Earth, about 4 billion years ago.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] For about 3 billion years, most organisms were microscopic, and bacteria and archaea were the dominant forms of life.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Although bacterial fossils exist, such as stromatolites, their lack of distinctive morphology prevents them from being used to examine the history of bacterial evolution, or to date the time of origin of a particular bacterial species.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] However, gene sequences can be used to reconstruct the bacterial phylogeny, and these studies indicate that bacteria diverged first from the archaeal/eukaryotic lineage.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The most recent common ancestor (MRCA) of bacteria and archaea was probably a hyperthermophile that lived about 2.5 billion–3.2 billion years ago.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The earliest life on land may have been bacteria some 3.22 billion years ago.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria were also involved in the second great evolutionary divergence, that of the archaea and eukaryotes.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Here, eukaryotes resulted from the entering of ancient bacteria into endosymbiotic associations with the ancestors of eukaryotic cells, which were themselves possibly related to the Archaea.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This involved the engulfment by proto-eukaryotic cells of alphaproteobacterial symbionts to form either mitochondria or hydrogenosomes, which are still found in all known Eukarya (sometimes in highly reduced form, e.g. in species of amitochondrial protozoa).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Later, some eukaryotes that already contained mitochondria also engulfed cyanobacteria-like organisms, leading to the formation of chloroplasts in algae and plants.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria are ubiquitous, living in every possible habitat on the planet including soil, underwater, deep in Earth's crust and even such extreme environments as acidic hot springs and radioactive waste.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] There are thought to be approximately 2×1030 bacteria on Earth, forming a biomass that is only exceeded by plants.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] They are abundant in lakes and oceans, in arctic ice, and geothermal springs where they provide the nutrients needed to sustain life by converting dissolved compounds, such as hydrogen sulphide and methane, to energy.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Most do not cause diseases, are beneficial to their environments, and are essential for life.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The soil is a rich source of bacteria and a few grams contain around a thousand million of them.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] They are all essential to soil ecology, breaking down toxic waste and recycling nutrients.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] They are even found in the atmosphere and one cubic metre of air holds around one hundred million bacterial cells.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The oceans and seas harbour around 3 × 1026 bacteria which provide up to 50% of the oxygen humans breathe.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Only around 2% of bacterial species have been fully studied.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria display a wide diversity of shapes and sizes.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cells are about one-tenth the size of eukaryotic cells and are typically 0.5–5.0 micrometres in length.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] However, a few species are visible to the unaided eye—for example, *Thiomargarita namibiensis* is up to half a millimetre long, *Epulopiscium fishelsoni* reaches 0.7 mm, and *Thiomargarita magnifica* can reach even 2 cm in length, which is 50 times larger than other known bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Among the smallest bacteria are members of the genus *Mycoplasma*, which measure only 0.3 micrometres, as small as the largest viruses.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria may be even smaller, but these ultramicrobacteria are not well-studied.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species are either spherical, called *cocci* (*singular coccus*, from Greek *kókkos*, grain, seed), or rod-shaped, called *bacilli* (*sing*. bacillus, from Latin *baculus*, stick).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, called *vibrio*, are shaped like slightly curved rods or comma-shaped; others can be spiral-shaped, called *spirilla*, or tightly coiled, called *spirochaetes*.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] A small number of other unusual shapes have been described, such as star-shaped bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This wide variety of shapes is determined by the bacterial cell wall and cytoskeleton and is important because it can influence the ability of bacteria to acquire nutrients, attach to surfaces, swim through liquids and escape predators.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species exist as single cells; others associate in characteristic patterns: *Neisseria* forms diploids (pairs), streptococci form chains, and staphylococci group together in "bunch of grapes" clusters.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can also group to form larger multicellular structures, such as the elongated filaments of *Actinomycetota* species, the aggregates of *Myxobacteria* species, and the complex hyphae of *Streptomyces* species.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] These multicellular structures are often only seen in certain conditions.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] For example, when starved of amino acids, myxobacteria detect surrounding cells in a process known as quorum sensing, migrate towards each other, and aggregate to form fruiting bodies up to 500 micrometres long and containing approximately 100,000 bacterial cells.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In these fruiting bodies, the bacteria perform separate tasks; for example, about one in ten cells migrate to the top of a fruiting body and differentiate into a specialised dormant state called a myxospore, which is more resistant to drying and other adverse environmental conditions.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often attach to surfaces and form dense aggregations called biofilms and larger formations known as microbial mats.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] These biofilms and mats can range from a few micrometres in thickness to up to half a metre in depth, and may contain multiple species of bacteria, protists and archaea.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria living in biofilms display a complex arrangement of cells and extracellular components, forming secondary structures, such as microcolonies, through which there are networks of channels to enable better diffusion of nutrients.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In natural environments, such as soil or the surfaces of plants, the majority of bacteria are bound to surfaces in biofilms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Biofilms are also important in medicine, as these structures are often present during chronic bacterial infections or in infections of implanted medical devices, and bacteria protected within biofilms are much harder to kill than individual isolated bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The bacterial cell is surrounded by a cell membrane, which is made primarily of phospholipids.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This membrane encloses the contents of the cell and acts as a barrier to hold nutrients, proteins and other essential components within the cell.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Unlike eukaryotic cells, bacteria usually lack large membrane-bound structures in their cytoplasm such as a nucleus, mitochondria, chloroplasts and the other organelles present in eukaryotic cells.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] However, some bacteria have protein-bound organelles in the cytoplasm which compartmentalise aspects of bacterial metabolism, such as the carboxysome.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Additionally, bacteria have a multi-component cytoskeleton to control the localisation of proteins and nucleic acids within the cell, and to manage the process of cell division.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Many important biochemical reactions, such as energy generation, occur due to differences in concentration of molecules across membranes, creating a electrochemical potential analogous to a battery.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The general lack of internal membranes in bacteria means these reactions, such as electron transport, occur across the cell membrane between the cytoplasm and the outside of the cell or periplasm.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] However, in many photosynthetic bacteria, the plasma membrane is highly folded and fills most of the cell with layers of light-gathering membrane.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] These light-gathering complexes may even form lipid-enclosed structures called chlorosomes in green sulfur bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria do not have a membrane-bound nucleus, and their genetic material is typically a single circular bacterial chromosome of DNA located in the cytoplasm in an irregularly shaped body called the nucleoid.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The nucleoid contains the chromosome with its associated proteins and RNA.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Like all other organisms, bacteria contain ribosomes for the production of proteins, but the structure of the bacterial ribosome is different from that of eukaryotes and archaea.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Its translation process is also different.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria produce intracellular nutrient storage granules, such as glycogen, polyphosphate, sulfur or polyhydroxyalkanoates.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria such as the photosynthetic cyanobacteria, produce internal gas vacuoles, which they use to regulate their buoyancy, allowing them to move up or down into water layers with different light intensities and nutrient levels.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Around the outside of the cell membrane is the cell wall.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are made of peptidoglycan (also called murein), which is made from polysaccharide chains cross-linked by peptides containing D-amino acids.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are different from the cell walls of plants and fungi, which are made of cellulose and chitin, respectively.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The cell wall of bacteria is also distinct from that of archaea, which do not contain peptidoglycan.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The cell wall is essential to the survival of many bacteria, and the antibiotic penicillin (produced by a fungus called *Penicillium*) is able to kill bacteria by inhibiting a step in the synthesis of peptidoglycan.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] There are broadly speaking two different types of cell wall in bacteria, that classify bacteria into Gram-positive bacteria and Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The names originate from the reaction of cells to the Gram stain, a long-standing test for the classification of bacterial species.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Gram-positive bacteria possess a thick cell wall containing many layers of peptidoglycan and teichoic acids.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In contrast, Gram-negative bacteria have a relatively thin cell wall consisting of a few layers of peptidoglycan surrounded by a second lipid membrane containing lipopolysaccharides and lipoproteins.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have the Gram-negative cell wall, and only members of the *Bacillota* group and actinomycetota (previously known as the low G+C and high G+C Gram-positive bacteria, respectively) have the alternative Gram-positive arrangement.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] These differences in structure can produce differences in antibiotic susceptibility; for instance, vancomycin can kill only Gram-positive bacteria and is ineffective against Gram-negative pathogens, such as *Haemophilus influenzae* or *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria have cell wall structures that are neither classically Gram-positive or Gram-negative.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This includes clinically important bacteria such as mycobacteria which have a thick peptidoglycan cell wall like a Gram-positive bacterium, but also a second outer layer of lipids.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In many bacteria, an S-layer of rigidly arrayed protein molecules covers the outside of the cell.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This layer provides chemical and physical protection for the cell surface and can act as a macromolecular diffusion barrier.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] S-layers have diverse functions and are known to act as virulence factors in *Campylobacter* species and contain surface enzymes in *Bacillus stearothermophilus*.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Flagella are rigid protein structures, about 20 nanometres in diameter and up to 20 micrometres in length, that are used for motility.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Flagella are driven by the energy released by the transfer of ions down an electrochemical gradient across the cell membrane.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae (sometimes called "attachment pili") are fine filaments of protein, usually 2–10 nanometres in diameter and up to several micrometres in length.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] They are distributed over the surface of the cell, and resemble fine hairs when seen under the electron microscope.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae are believed to be involved in attachment to solid surfaces or to other cells, and are essential for the virulence of some bacterial pathogens.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Pili (*sing*. pilus) are cellular appendages, slightly larger than fimbriae, that can transfer genetic material between bacterial cells in a process called conjugation where they are called conjugation pili or sex pili (see bacterial genetics, below).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] They can also generate movement where they are called type IV pili.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Glycocalyx is produced by many bacteria to surround their cells, and varies in structural complexity: ranging from a disorganised slime layer of extracellular polymeric substances to a highly structured capsule.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] These structures can protect cells from engulfment by eukaryotic cells such as macrophages (part of the human immune system).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] They can also act as antigens and be involved in cell recognition, as well as aiding attachment to surfaces and the formation of biofilms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The assembly of these extracellular structures is dependent on bacterial secretion systems.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] These transfer proteins from the cytoplasm into the periplasm or into the environment around the cell.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Many types of secretion systems are known and these structures are often essential for the virulence of pathogens, so are intensively studied.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Some genera of Gram-positive bacteria, such as *Bacillus*, *Clostridium*, *Sporohalobacter*, *Anaerobacter*, and *Heliobacterium*, can form highly resistant, dormant structures called *endospores*.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Endospores develop within the cytoplasm of the cell; generally, a single endospore develops in each cell.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Each endospore contains a core of DNA and ribosomes surrounded by a cortex layer and protected by a multilayer rigid coat composed of peptidoglycan and a variety of proteins.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Endospores show no detectable metabolism and can survive extreme physical and chemical stresses, such as high levels of UV light, gamma radiation, detergents, disinfectants, heat, freezing, pressure, and desiccation.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In this dormant state, these organisms may remain viable for millions of years.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Endospores even allow bacteria to survive exposure to the vacuum and radiation of outer space, leading to the possibility that bacteria could be distributed throughout the universe by space dust, meteoroids, asteroids, comets, planetoids, or directed panspermia.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] *Clostridioides difficile* infection, a common problem in healthcare settings, is caused by spore-forming bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria exhibit an extremely wide variety of metabolic types.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The distribution of metabolic traits within a group of bacteria has traditionally been used to define their taxonomy, but these traits often do not correspond with modern genetic classifications.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolism is classified into nutritional groups on the basis of three major criteria: the source of energy, the electron donors used, and the source of carbon used for growth.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Phototrophic bacteria derive energy from light using photosynthesis, while chemotrophic bacteria breaking down chemical compounds through oxidation, driving metabolism by transferring electrons from a given electron donor to a terminal electron acceptor in a redox reaction.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Chemotrophs are further divided by the types of compounds they use to transfer electrons.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria that derive electrons from inorganic compounds such as hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or ammonia are called lithotrophs, while those that use organic compounds are called organotrophs.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Still, more specifically, aerobic organisms use oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor, while anaerobic organisms use other compounds such as nitrate, sulfate, or carbon dioxide.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria, called heterotrophs, derive their carbon from other organic carbon.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Others, such as cyanobacteria and some purple bacteria, are autotrophic, meaning they obtain cellular carbon by fixing carbon dioxide.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In unusual circumstances, the gas methane can be used by methanotrophic bacteria as both a source of electrons and a substrate for carbon anabolism.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In many ways, bacterial metabolism provides traits that are useful for ecological stability and for human society.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] For example, diazotrophs have the ability to fix nitrogen gas using the enzyme nitrogenase.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This trait, which can be found in bacteria of most metabolic types listed above, leads to the ecologically important processes of denitrification, sulfate reduction, and acetogenesis, respectively.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolic processes are important drivers in biological responses to pollution; for example, sulfate-reducing bacteria are largely responsible for the production of the highly toxic forms of mercury (methyl- and dimethylmercury) in the environment.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Nonrespiratory anaerobes use fermentation to generate energy and reducing power, secreting metabolic by-products (such as ethanol in brewing) as waste.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Facultative anaerobes can switch between fermentation and different terminal electron acceptors depending on the environmental conditions in which they find themselves.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Unlike in multicellular organisms, increases in cell size (cell growth) and reproduction by cell division are tightly linked in unicellular organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria grow to a fixed size and then reproduce through binary fission, a form of asexual reproduction.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Under optimal conditions, bacteria can grow and divide extremely rapidly, and some bacterial populations can double as quickly as every 17 minutes.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In cell division, two identical clone daughter cells are produced.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, while still reproducing asexually, form more complex reproductive structures that help disperse the newly formed daughter cells.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Examples include fruiting body formation by myxobacteria and aerial hyphae formation by *Streptomyces* species, or budding.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Budding involves a cell forming a protrusion that breaks away and produces a daughter cell.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In the laboratory, bacteria are usually grown using solid or liquid media.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Solid growth media, such as agar plates, are used to isolate pure cultures of a bacterial strain.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] However, liquid growth media are used when the measurement of growth or large volumes of cells are required.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Growth in stirred liquid media occurs as an even cell suspension, making the cultures easy to divide and transfer, although isolating single bacteria from liquid media is difficult.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The use of selective media (media with specific nutrients added or deficient, or with antibiotics added) can help identify specific organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Most laboratory techniques for growing bacteria use high levels of nutrients to produce large amounts of cells cheaply and quickly.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] However, in natural environments, nutrients are limited, meaning that bacteria cannot continue to reproduce indefinitely.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This nutrient limitation has led the evolution of different growth strategies (see r/K selection theory).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Some organisms can grow extremely rapidly when nutrients become available, such as the formation of algal and cyanobacterial blooms that often occur in lakes during the summer.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Other organisms have adaptations to harsh environments, such as the production of multiple antibiotics by *Streptomyces* that inhibit the growth of competing microorganisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In nature, many organisms live in communities (e.g., biofilms) that may allow for increased supply of nutrients and protection from environmental stresses.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] These relationships can be essential for growth of a particular organism or group of organisms (syntrophy).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] When a population of bacteria first enter a high-nutrient environment that allows growth, the cells need to adapt to their new environment.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The first phase of growth is the lag phase, a period of slow growth when the cells are adapting to the high-nutrient environment and preparing for fast growth.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The lag phase has high biosynthesis rates, as proteins necessary for rapid growth are produced.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The second phase of growth is the logarithmic phase, also known as the exponential phase.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The log phase is marked by rapid exponential growth.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The rate at which cells grow during this phase is known as the *growth rate* (*k*), and the time it takes the cells to double is known as the *generation time* (*g*).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] During log phase, nutrients are metabolised at maximum speed until one of the nutrients is depleted and starts limiting growth.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The third phase of growth is the *stationary phase* and is caused by depleted nutrients.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The cells reduce their metabolic activity and consume non-essential cellular proteins.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The stationary phase is a transition from rapid growth to a stress response state and there is increased expression of genes involved in DNA repair, antioxidant metabolism and nutrient transport.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The final phase is the death phase where the bacteria run out of nutrients and die.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] There are many exceptions to this; for example, some *Streptomyces* and *Borrelia* species contain a single linear chromosome, while some bacteria including species of *Vibrio* contain more than one chromosome.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria contain plasmids, small extra-chromosomal molecules of DNA that may contain genes for various useful functions such as antibiotic resistance, metabolic capabilities, or various virulence factors.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Whether they have a single chromosome or more than one, almost all bacteria have a haploid genome.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This means that they have only one copy of each gene encoding proteins.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This is in contrast to eukaryotes, which are diploid or polyploid, meaning they have two or more copies of each gene.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This means that unlike humans, who may still be able to create a protein if the gene becomes mutated (since the human genome has an extra copy in each cell), a bacterium will be completely unable to create the protein if its gene incurs an inactivating mutation.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacterial genomes usually encode a few hundred to a few thousand genes.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The genes in bacterial genomes are usually a single continuous stretch of DNA.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Although several different types of introns do exist in bacteria, these are much rarer than in eukaryotes.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria, as asexual organisms, inherit an identical copy of the parent's genome and are clonal.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] However, all bacteria can evolve by selection on changes to their genetic material DNA caused by genetic recombination or mutations.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Mutations arise from errors made during the replication of DNA or from exposure to mutagens.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Mutation rates vary widely among different species of bacteria and even among different clones of a single species of bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Genetic changes in bacterial genomes emerge from either random mutation during replication or "stress-directed mutation", where genes involved in a particular growth-limiting process have an increased mutation rate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria transfer genetic material between cells.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] First, bacteria can take up exogenous DNA from their environment in a process called transformation.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria can naturally take up DNA from the environment, while others must be chemically altered in order to induce them to take up DNA.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The development of competence in nature is usually associated with stressful environmental conditions and seems to be an adaptation for facilitating repair of DNA damage in recipient cells.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Second, bacteriophages can integrate into the bacterial chromosome, introducing foreign DNA in a process known as transduction.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Many types of bacteriophage exist; some infect and lyse their host bacteria, while others insert into the bacterial chromosome.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Third, bacteria can transfer genetic material through direct cell contact via conjugation.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In such cases, gene acquisition from other bacteria or the environment is called horizontal gene transfer and may be common under natural conditions.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria are motile (able to move themselves) and do so using a variety of mechanisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The best studied of these are flagella, long filaments that are turned by a motor at the base to generate propeller-like movement.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The bacterial flagellum is made of about 20 proteins, with approximately another 30 proteins required for its regulation and assembly.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The flagellum is a rotating structure driven by a reversible motor at the base that uses the electrochemical gradient across the membrane for power.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can use flagella in different ways to generate different kinds of movement.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria (such as *E. coli*) have two distinct modes of movement: forward movement (swimming) and tumbling.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The tumbling allows them to reorient and makes their movement a three-dimensional random walk.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The flagella of a group of bacteria, the spirochaetes, are found between two membranes in the periplasmic space.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] They have a distinctive helical body that twists about as it moves.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Two other types of bacterial motion are called twitching motility that relies on a structure called the type IV pilus, and gliding motility, that uses other mechanisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In twitching motility, the rod-like pilus extends out from the cell, binds some substrate, and then retracts, pulling the cell forward.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Motile bacteria are attracted or repelled by certain stimuli in behaviours called *taxes*: these include chemotaxis, phototaxis, energy taxis, and magnetotaxis.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] In one peculiar group, the myxobacteria, individual bacteria move together to form waves of cells that then differentiate to form fruiting bodies containing spores.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The myxobacteria move only when on solid surfaces, unlike *E. coli*, which is motile in liquid or solid media.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Several *Listeria* and *Shigella* species move inside host cells by usurping the cytoskeleton, which is normally used to move organelles inside the cell.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] By promoting actin polymerisation at one pole of their cells, they can form a kind of tail that pushes them through the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] A few bacteria have chemical systems that generate light.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This bioluminescence often occurs in bacteria that live in association with fish, and the light probably serves to attract fish or other large animals.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often function as multicellular aggregates known as biofilms, exchanging a variety of molecular signals for intercell communication and engaging in coordinated multicellular behaviour.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The communal benefits of multicellular cooperation include a cellular division of labour, accessing resources that cannot effectively be used by single cells, collectively defending against antagonists, and optimising population survival by differentiating into distinct cell types.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] For example, bacteria in biofilms can have more than five hundred times the increased resistance to antibacterial agents than individual "planktonic" bacteria of the same species.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] One type of intercellular communication by a molecular signal is called quorum sensing.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing determines whether the local population is dense enough to support investment in processes that are only successful if large numbers of similar organisms behave similarly, such as excreting digestive enzymes or emitting light.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing enables bacteria to coordinate gene expression and to produce, release, and detect autoinducers or pheromones that accumulate with the growth in cell population.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Classification seeks to describe the diversity of bacterial species by naming and grouping organisms based on similarities.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can be classified on the basis of cell structure, cellular metabolism or on differences in cell components, such as DNA, fatty acids, pigments, antigens and quinones.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] While these schemes allowed the identification and classification of **bacterial strains**, it was unclear whether these differences represented variation between distinct species or between strains of the same species.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This uncertainty was due to the lack of distinctive structures in most bacteria, as well as lateral gene transfer between unrelated species.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Due to lateral gene transfer, some closely related bacteria can have very different morphologies and metabolisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Classification of bacteria is determined by publication in the International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology, and Bergey's Manual of Systematic Bacteriology.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The International Committee on Systematic Bacteriology (ICSB) maintains international rules for the naming of bacteria and taxonomic categories and for the ranking of them in the International Code of Nomenclature of Bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Historically, bacteria were considered a part of the Plantae, the plant kingdom, and were called "Schizomycetes" (fission-fungi).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] For this reason, collective bacteria and other microorganisms in a host are often called "flora".
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The term "bacteria" was traditionally applied to all microscopic, single-cell prokaryotes.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] However, molecular systematics showed prokaryotic life to consist of two separate domains, originally called Eubacteria and Archaebacteria, but now called Bacteria and Archaea that evolved independently from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The archaea and eukaryotes are more closely related to each other than either is to the bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] These two domains, along with Eukarya, are the basis of the three-domain system, which is currently the most widely used classification system in microbiology.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] However, due to the relatively recent introduction of molecular systematics and a rapid increase in the number of genome sequences that are available, bacterial classification remains a changing and expanding field.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] For example, Cavalier-Smith argued that the Archaea and Eukaryotes evolved from Gram-positive bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The identification of bacteria in the laboratory is particularly relevant in medicine, where the correct treatment is determined by the bacterial species causing an infection.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Consequently, the need to identify human pathogens was a major impetus for the development of techniques to identify bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Once a pathogenic organism has been isolated, it can be further characterised by its morphology, growth patterns (such as aerobic or anaerobic growth), patterns of hemolysis, and staining.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The *Gram stain*, developed in 1884 by Hans Christian Gram, characterises bacteria based on the structural characteristics of their cell walls.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The thick layers of peptidoglycan in the "Gram-positive" cell wall stain purple, while the thin "Gram-negative" cell wall appears pink.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] By combining morphology and Gram-staining, most bacteria can be classified as belonging to one of four groups (Gram-positive cocci, Gram-positive bacilli, Gram-negative cocci and Gram-negative bacilli).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Some organisms are best identified by stains other than the Gram stain, particularly mycobacteria or *Nocardia*, which show acid fastness on Ziehl–Neelsen or similar stains.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Culture techniques are designed to promote the growth and identify particular bacteria while restricting the growth of the other bacteria in the sample.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Often these techniques are designed for specific specimens; for example, a sputum sample will be treated to identify organisms that cause pneumonia, while stool specimens are cultured on selective media to identify organisms that cause diarrhea while preventing growth of non-pathogenic bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Specimens that are normally sterile, such as blood, urine or spinal fluid, are cultured under conditions designed to grow all possible organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Other organisms may need to be identified by their growth in special media, or by other techniques, such as serology.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] As with bacterial classification, identification of bacteria is increasingly using molecular methods, and mass spectroscopy.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have not been characterised and there are many species that cannot be grown in the laboratory.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Diagnostics using DNA-based tools, such as polymerase chain reaction, are increasingly popular due to their specificity and speed, compared to culture-based methods.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] These methods also allow the detection and identification of "viable but nonculturable" cells that are metabolically active but non-dividing.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] The main way to characterize and classify these bacteria is to isolate their DNA from environmental samples and mass-sequence them.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] This approach has identified thousands, if not millions of candidate species.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p01] Based on some estimates, more than 43,000 species of bacteria have been described, but attempts to estimate the true number of bacterial diversity have ranged from 107 to 109 total species—and even these diverse estimates may be off by many orders of magnitude.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Despite their apparent simplicity, bacteria can form complex associations with other organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] These symbiotic associations can be divided into parasitism, mutualism and commensalism.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] The word "commensalism" is derived from the word "commensal", meaning "eating at the same table" and all plants and animals are colonised by commensal bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] In humans and other animals, trillions of them live on the skin, the airways, the gut and other orifices.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Referred to as "normal flora", or "commensals", these bacteria usually cause no harm but may occasionally invade other sites of the body and cause infection.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] *Escherichia coli* is a commensal in the human gut but can cause urinary tract infections.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Similarly, streptococci, which are part of the normal flora of the human mouth, can cause heart disease.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Some species of bacteria kill and then consume other microorganisms; these species are called *predatory bacteria*.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] These include organisms such as *Myxococcus xanthus*, which forms swarms of cells that kill and digest any bacteria they encounter.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Other bacterial predators either attach to their prey in order to digest them and absorb nutrients or invade another cell and multiply inside the cytosol.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] These predatory bacteria are thought to have evolved from saprophages that consumed dead microorganisms, through adaptations that allowed them to entrap and kill other organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Certain bacteria form close spatial associations that are essential for their survival.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] One such mutualistic association, called interspecies hydrogen transfer, occurs between clusters of anaerobic bacteria that consume organic acids, such as butyric acid or propionic acid, and produce hydrogen, and methanogenic archaea that consume hydrogen.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] The bacteria in this association are unable to consume the organic acids as this reaction produces hydrogen that accumulates in their surroundings.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Only the intimate association with the hydrogen-consuming archaea keeps the hydrogen concentration low enough to allow the bacteria to grow.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] In soil, microorganisms that reside in the rhizosphere (a zone that includes the root surface and the soil that adheres to the root after gentle shaking) carry out nitrogen fixation, converting nitrogen gas to nitrogenous compounds.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] This serves to provide an easily absorbable form of nitrogen for many plants, which cannot fix nitrogen themselves.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Many other bacteria are found as symbionts in humans and other organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] The presence of this gut flora also inhibits the growth of potentially pathogenic bacteria (usually through competitive exclusion) and these beneficial bacteria are consequently sold as probiotic dietary supplements.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Nearly all animal life is dependent on bacteria for survival as only bacteria and some archaea possess the genes and enzymes necessary to synthesise vitamin B12, also known as cobalamin, and provide it through the food chain.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Vitamin B12 is a water-soluble vitamin that is involved in the metabolism of every cell of the human body.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] It is a cofactor in DNA synthesis and in both fatty acid and amino acid metabolism.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] It is particularly important in the normal functioning of the nervous system via its role in the synthesis of myelin.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] The body is continually exposed to many species of bacteria, including beneficial commensals, which grow on the skin and mucous membranes, and saprophytes, which grow mainly in the soil and in decaying matter.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] The blood and tissue fluids contain nutrients sufficient to sustain the growth of many bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] The body has defence mechanisms that enable it to resist microbial invasion of its tissues and give it a natural immunity or innate resistance against many microorganisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Unlike some viruses, bacteria evolve relatively slowly so many bacterial diseases also occur in other animals.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] If bacteria form a parasitic association with other organisms, they are classed as pathogens.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] A pathogenic cause for a known medical disease may only be discovered many years later, as was the case with *Helicobacter pylori* and peptic ulcer disease.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Bacterial diseases are also important in agriculture, and bacteria cause leaf spot, fire blight and wilts in plants, as well as Johne's disease, mastitis, salmonella and anthrax in farm animals.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Each species of pathogen has a characteristic spectrum of interactions with its human hosts.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Some organisms, such as *Staphylococcus* or *Streptococcus*, can cause skin infections, pneumonia, meningitis and sepsis, a systemic inflammatory response producing shock, massive vasodilation and death.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Yet these organisms are also part of the normal human flora and usually exist on the skin or in the nose without causing any disease at all.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Other organisms invariably cause disease in humans, such as *Rickettsia*, which are obligate intracellular parasites able to grow and reproduce only within the cells of other organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] One species of *Rickettsia* causes typhus, while another causes Rocky Mountain spotted fever.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] *Chlamydia*, another phylum of obligate intracellular parasites, contains species that can cause pneumonia or urinary tract infection and may be involved in coronary heart disease.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Some species, such as *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, *Burkholderia cenocepacia*, and *Mycobacterium avium*, are opportunistic pathogens and cause disease mainly in people who are immunosuppressed or have cystic fibrosis.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Some bacteria produce toxins, which cause diseases.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] These are endotoxins, which come from broken bacterial cells, and exotoxins, which are produced by bacteria and released into the environment.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] The bacterium *Clostridium botulinum* for example, produces a powerful exotoxin that cause respiratory paralysis, and *Salmonellae* produce an endotoxin that causes gastroenteritis.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Some exotoxins can be converted to toxoids, which are used as vaccines to prevent the disease.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Bacterial infections may be treated with antibiotics, which are classified as bacteriocidal if they kill bacteria or bacteriostatic if they just prevent bacterial growth.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] There are many types of antibiotics, and each class inhibits a process that is different in the pathogen from that found in the host.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] An example of how antibiotics produce selective toxicity are chloramphenicol and puromycin, which inhibit the bacterial ribosome, but not the structurally different eukaryotic ribosome.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Antibiotics are used both in treating human disease and in intensive farming to promote animal growth, where they may be contributing to the rapid development of antibiotic resistance in bacterial populations.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Infections can be prevented by antiseptic measures such as sterilising the skin prior to piercing it with the needle of a syringe, and by proper care of indwelling catheters.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Surgical and dental instruments are also sterilised to prevent contamination by bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Disinfectants such as bleach are used to kill bacteria or other pathogens on surfaces to prevent contamination and further reduce the risk of infection.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Bacteria, often lactic acid bacteria, such as *Lactobacillus* species and *Lactococcus* species, in combination with yeasts and moulds, have been used for thousands of years in the preparation of fermented foods, such as cheese, pickles, soy sauce, sauerkraut, vinegar, wine, and yogurt.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] The ability of bacteria to degrade a variety of organic compounds is remarkable and has been used in waste processing and bioremediation.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Bacteria capable of digesting the hydrocarbons in petroleum are often used to clean up oil spills.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Fertiliser was added to some of the beaches in Prince William Sound in an attempt to promote the growth of these naturally occurring bacteria after the 1989 *Exxon Valdez* oil spill.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] These efforts were effective on beaches that were not too thickly covered in oil.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Bacteria are also used for the bioremediation of industrial toxic wastes.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] In the chemical industry, bacteria are most important in the production of enantiomerically pure chemicals for use as pharmaceuticals or agrichemicals.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Bacteria can also be used in place of pesticides in biological pest control.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] This commonly involves *Bacillus thuringiensis* (also called BT), a Gram-positive, soil-dwelling bacterium.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Subspecies of this bacteria are used as Lepidopteran-specific insecticides under trade names such as Dipel and Thuricide.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Because of their specificity, these pesticides are regarded as environmentally friendly, with little or no effect on humans, wildlife, pollinators, and most other beneficial insects.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Because of their ability to quickly grow and the relative ease with which they can be manipulated, bacteria are the workhorses for the fields of molecular biology, genetics, and biochemistry.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] By making mutations in bacterial DNA and examining the resulting phenotypes, scientists can determine the function of genes, enzymes, and metabolic pathways in bacteria, then apply this knowledge to more complex organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] This aim of understanding the biochemistry of a cell reaches its most complex expression in the synthesis of huge amounts of enzyme kinetic and gene expression data into mathematical models of entire organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] This is achievable in some well-studied bacteria, with models of *Escherichia coli* metabolism now being produced and tested.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] This understanding of bacterial metabolism and genetics allows the use of biotechnology to bioengineer bacteria for the production of therapeutic proteins, such as insulin, growth factors, or antibodies.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Because of their importance for research in general, samples of bacterial strains are isolated and preserved in Biological Resource Centres.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] This ensures the availability of the strain to scientists worldwide.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were first observed by the Dutch microscopist Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1676, using a single-lens microscope of his own design.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Leeuwenhoek did not recognize bacteria as a distinct category of microorganisms, referring to all microorganisms that he observed, including bacteria, protists, and microscopic animals, as animalcules.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] He published his observations in a series of letters to the Royal Society of London.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were Leeuwenhoek's most remarkable microscopic discovery.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Their size was just at the limit of what his simple lenses could resolve, and, in one of the most striking hiatuses in the history of science, no one else would see them again for over a century.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] His observations also included protozoans, and his findings were looked at again in the light of the more recent findings of cell theory.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg introduced the word "bacterium" in 1828.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] In fact, his *Bacterium* was a genus that contained non-spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria, as opposed to *Bacillus*, a genus of spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria defined by Ehrenberg in 1835.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Louis Pasteur demonstrated in 1859 that the growth of microorganisms causes the fermentation process and that this growth is not due to spontaneous generation (yeasts and molds, commonly associated with fermentation, are not bacteria, but rather fungi).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Along with his contemporary Robert Koch, Pasteur was an early advocate of the germ theory of disease.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Before them, Ignaz Semmelweis and Joseph Lister had realised the importance of sanitised hands in medical work.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Semmelweis, who in the 1840s formulated his rules for handwashing in the hospital, prior to the advent of germ theory, attributed disease to "decomposing animal organic matter".
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] His ideas were rejected and his book on the topic condemned by the medical community.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] After Lister, however, doctors started sanitising their hands in the 1870s.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Robert Koch, a pioneer in medical microbiology, worked on cholera, anthrax and tuberculosis.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] In his research into tuberculosis, Koch finally proved the germ theory, for which he received a Nobel Prize in 1905.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] In Koch's postulates, he set out criteria to test if an organism is the cause of a disease, and these postulates are still used today.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Ferdinand Cohn is said to be a founder of bacteriology, studying bacteria from 1870.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Cohn was the first to classify bacteria based on their morphology.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Though it was known in the nineteenth century that bacteria are the cause of many diseases, no effective antibacterial treatments were available.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] In 1910, Paul Ehrlich developed the first antibiotic, by changing dyes that selectively stained *Treponema pallidum*—the spirochaete that causes syphilis—into compounds that selectively killed the pathogen.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] Ehrlich, who had been awarded a 1908 Nobel Prize for his work on immunology, pioneered the use of stains to detect and identify bacteria, with his work being the basis of the Gram stain and the Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] A major step forward in the study of bacteria came in 1977 when Carl Woese recognised that archaea have a separate line of evolutionary descent from bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacteria-p02] This new phylogenetic taxonomy depended on the sequencing of 16S ribosomal RNA and divided prokaryotes into two evolutionary domains, as part of the three-domain system.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] It has been estimated that ~1,300 bacterial phyla exist.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] As of May 2020, 41 bacterial phyla are formally accepted by the LPSN, 89 bacterial phyla are recognized on the Silva database, dozens more have been proposed, and hundreds likely remain to be discovered.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] As of 2017, approximately 72% of widely recognized bacterial phyla were candidate phyla (i.e. have no cultured representatives).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] The rank of phylum has been included in the rules of the International Code of Nomenclature of Prokaryotes, using the ending *–ota* for phylum names that must be based on the name of a genus as its nomenclatural type.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] The following is a list of bacterial phyla that have been validly published as of December 2023.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] The following is a list of candidate phyla that have not been cultured.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] Despite the unclear branching order for most bacterial phyla, several groups of phyla consistently cluster together and are referred to as supergroups or superphyla.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] In some instances, bacterial clades clearly consistently cluster together but it is unclear what to call the group.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] For example, the Candidate Phyla Radiation includes the Patescibacteria group which includes Microgenomates group which includes over 11 bacterial phyla.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] The LPSN recognizes four kingdoms of bacteria as validly published: Bacillati, Fusobacteriati, Pseudomonadati and Thermotogati.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] The CPR is a descriptive term referring to a massive monophyletic radiation of candidate phyla that exists within the Bacterial domain.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] It includes two main clades, the Microgenomates and Parcubacteria groups, each containing the eponymous superphyla and a few other phyla.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] The superphylum Patescibacteria was originally proposed to encompass the phyla Microgenomates (OP11), Parcubacteria (OD1), and Gracilibacteria (GNO2 / BD1-5).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] More recent phylogenetic analyses show that the last common ancestor of these taxa is the same node as that of CPR.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] The Sphingobacteria (FCB group) includes Bacteroidota, Calditrichota, Chlorobiota, candidate phylum "Cloacimonetes", Fibrobacterota, Gemmatimonadota, Ignavibacteriota, candidate phylum "Latescibacteria", candidate phylum "Marinimicrobia", and candidate phylum "Zixibacteria".
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] Parcubacteria was originally described as a single phylum using fewer than 100 16S rRNA sequences.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] With a greater diversity of 16S rRNA sequences from uncultured organisms now available, it is estimated it may consist of up to 28 bacterial phyla.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] In line with this, over 14 phyla have now been described within the Parcubacteria group, including Kaiserbacteria, Adlerbacteria, Campbellbacteria, Nomurabacteria, Giovannonibacteria, Wolfebacteria, Jorgensenbacteria, Yanofskybacteria, Azambacteria, Moranbacteria, Uhrbacteria, and Magasanikbacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] It has been proposed that some classes of the phylum Proteobacteria may be phyla in their own right, which would make Proteobacteria a superphylum.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] For example, the Deltaproteobacteria group does not consistently form a monophyletic lineage with the other Proteobacteria classes.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] The Planctobacteria (PVC group) includes Chlamydiota, Lentisphaerota, candidate phylum "Omnitrophica", Planctomycetota, candidate phylum "Poribacteria", and Verrucomicrobiota.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] The kingdom Bacillati, includes Actinomycetota, "Cyanobacteria/Melainabacteria clade", Deinococcota, Chloroflexota, Bacillota, and candidate phylum OP10.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] For example, it is suggested that candidate phylum Parcubacteria is actually a superphylum that encompasses 28 subordinate phyla and that phylum Elusimicrobia is actually a superphylum that encompasses 7 subordinate phyla.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] Given the rich history of the field of bacterial taxonomy and the rapidity of changes therein in modern times, it is often useful to have a historical perspective on how the field has progressed in order to understand references to antiquated definitions or concepts.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] When bacterial nomenclature was controlled under the Botanical Code, the term *division* was used, but now that bacterial nomenclature (with the exception of cyanobacteria) is controlled under the Bacteriological Code, the term *phylum* is preferred.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] In 1987, Carl Woese, regarded as the forerunner of the molecular phylogeny revolution, divided Eubacteria into 11 divisions based on 16S ribosomal RNA (SSU) sequences, listed below.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] Traditionally, phylogeny was inferred and taxonomy established based on studies of morphology.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] The advent of molecular phylogenetics has allowed for improved elucidation of the evolutionary relationship of species by analyzing their DNA and protein sequences, for example their ribosomal DNA.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] Many bacterial taxa were re-classified or re-defined using molecular phylogenetics.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] The advent of molecular sequencing technologies has allowed for the recovery of genomes directly from environmental samples (i.e. bypassing culturing), leading to rapid expansion of our knowledge of the diversity of bacterial phyla.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/bacterial-phyla] These techniques are genome-resolved metagenomics and single-cell genomics.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Early Greeks established the core idea of biogeochemistry that nature consists of cycles.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Agricultural interest in 18th-century soil chemistry led to better understanding of nutrients and their connection to biochemical processes.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] This relationship between the cycles of organic life and their chemical products was further expanded upon by Dumas and Boussingault in a 1844 paper that is considered an important milestone in the development of biogeochemistry.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Jean-Baptiste Lamarck first used the term *biosphere* in 1802, and others continued to develop the concept throughout the 19th century.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Early climate research by scientists like Charles Lyell, John Tyndall, and Joseph Fourier began to link glaciation, weathering, and climate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] The founder of modern biogeochemistry was Vladimir Vernadsky, a Russian and Ukrainian scientist whose 1926 book *The Biosphere*, in the tradition of Mendeleev, formulated a physics of the Earth as a living whole.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Vernadsky distinguished three spheres, where a sphere was a concept similar to the concept of a phase-space.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Human activities (e.g., agriculture and industry) modify the biosphere and abiotic sphere.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] In the contemporary environment, the amount of influence humans have on the other two spheres is comparable to a geological force (see Anthropocene).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] The American limnologist and geochemist G.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Evelyn Hutchinson is credited with outlining the broad scope and principles of this new field.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] More recently, the basic elements of the discipline of biogeochemistry were restated and popularized by the British scientist and writer, James Lovelock, under the label of the *Gaia Hypothesis*.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Lovelock emphasized a concept that life processes regulate the Earth through feedback mechanisms to keep it habitable.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] The research of Manfred Schidlowski was concerned with the biochemistry of the Early Earth.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Biogeochemical cycles are the pathways by which chemical substances cycle (are turned over or moved through) the biotic and the abiotic compartments of Earth.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] The biotic compartment is the biosphere and the abiotic compartments are the atmosphere, hydrosphere and lithosphere.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] There are biogeochemical cycles for chemical elements, such as for calcium, carbon, hydrogen, mercury, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, selenium, iron and sulfur, as well as molecular cycles, such as for water and silica.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] There are also macroscopic cycles, such as the rock cycle, and human-induced cycles for synthetic compounds such as polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] In some cycles there are reservoirs where a substance can remain or be sequestered for a long period of time.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Biogeochemistry research groups exist in many universities around the world.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Since this is a highly interdisciplinary field, these are situated within a wide range of host disciplines including: atmospheric sciences, biology, ecology, geomicrobiology, environmental chemistry, geology, oceanography and soil science.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] These are often bracketed into larger disciplines such as earth science and environmental science.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Many researchers investigate the biogeochemical cycles of chemical elements such as carbon, oxygen, nitrogen, phosphorus and sulfur, as well as their stable isotopes.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] The cycles of trace elements, such as the trace metals and the radionuclides, are also studied.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] This research has obvious applications in the exploration of ore deposits and oil, and in the remediation of environmental pollution.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] Evolutionary biogeochemistry is a branch of modern biogeochemistry that applies the study of biogeochemical cycles to the geologic history of the Earth.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biogeochemistry] This field investigates the origin of biogeochemical cycles and how they have changed throughout the planet's history, specifically in relation to the evolution of life.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Elements of biosynthesis include: precursor compounds, chemical energy (e.g.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] ATP), and catalytic enzymes which may need coenzymes (e.g.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] These elements create monomers, the building blocks for macromolecules.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Some important biological macromolecules include: proteins, which are composed of amino acid monomers joined via peptide bonds, and DNA molecules, which are composed of nucleotides joined via phosphodiester bonds.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Biosynthesis occurs due to a series of chemical reactions.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Simple compounds that are converted into other compounds with the assistance of cofactors.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] For example, the synthesis of phospholipids requires acetyl CoA, while the synthesis of another membrane component, sphingolipids, requires NADH and FADH for the formation the sphingosine backbone.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Simple compounds that join to create a macromolecule.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] For example, fatty acids join to form phospholipids.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In turn, phospholipids and cholesterol interact noncovalently in order to form the lipid bilayer.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Many intricate macromolecules are synthesized in a pattern of simple, repeated structures.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] For example, the simplest structures of lipids are fatty acids.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Fatty acids are hydrocarbon derivatives; they contain a carboxyl group "head" and a hydrocarbon chain "tail".
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] These fatty acids create larger components, which in turn incorporate noncovalent interactions to form the lipid bilayer.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Fatty acid chains are found in two major components of membrane lipids: phospholipids and sphingolipids.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] A third major membrane component, cholesterol, does not contain these fatty acid units.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The foundation of all biomembranes consists of a bilayer structure of phospholipids.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The phospholipid molecule is amphipathic; it contains a hydrophilic polar head and a hydrophobic nonpolar tail.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The phospholipid heads interact with each other and aqueous media, while the hydrocarbon tails orient themselves in the center, away from water.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] These latter interactions drive the bilayer structure that acts as a barrier for ions and molecules.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] There are various types of phospholipids; consequently, their synthesis pathways differ.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] However, the first step in phospholipid synthesis involves the formation of phosphatidate or diacylglycerol 3-phosphate at the endoplasmic reticulum and outer mitochondrial membrane.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The pathway starts with glycerol 3-phosphate, which gets converted to lysophosphatidate via the addition of a fatty acid chain provided by acyl coenzyme A.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Then, lysophosphatidate is converted to phosphatidate via the addition of another fatty acid chain contributed by a second acyl CoA; all of these steps are catalyzed by the glycerol phosphate acyltransferase enzyme.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Phospholipid synthesis continues in the endoplasmic reticulum, and the biosynthesis pathway diverges depending on the components of the particular phospholipid.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Like phospholipids, these fatty acid derivatives have a polar head and nonpolar tails.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Unlike phospholipids, sphingolipids have a sphingosine backbone.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Sphingolipids exist in eukaryotic cells and are particularly abundant in the central nervous system.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] For example, sphingomyelin is part of the myelin sheath of nerve fibers.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Sphingolipids are formed from ceramides that consist of a fatty acid chain attached to the amino group of a sphingosine backbone.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] These ceramides are synthesized from the acylation of sphingosine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] As the image denotes, during sphingosine synthesis, palmitoyl CoA and serine undergo a condensation reaction which results in the formation of 3-dehydrosphinganine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This product is then reduced to form dihydrospingosine, which is converted to sphingosine via the oxidation reaction by FAD.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This lipid belongs to a class of molecules called sterols.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Sterols have four fused rings and a hydroxyl group.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Cholesterol is a particularly important molecule.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Not only does it serve as a component of lipid membranes, it is also a precursor to several steroid hormones, including cortisol, testosterone, and estrogen.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Cholesterol is synthesized from acetyl CoA.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] More generally, this synthesis occurs in three stages, with the first stage taking place in the cytoplasm and the second and third stages occurring in the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The biosynthesis of nucleotides involves enzyme-catalyzed reactions that convert substrates into more complex products.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Nucleotides are the building blocks of DNA and RNA.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Nucleotides are composed of a five-membered ring formed from ribose sugar in RNA, and deoxyribose sugar in DNA; these sugars are linked to a purine or pyrimidine base with a glycosidic bond and a phosphate group at the 5' location of the sugar.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The DNA nucleotides adenosine and guanosine consist of a purine base attached to a ribose sugar with a glycosidic bond.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In the case of RNA nucleotides deoxyadenosine and deoxyguanosine, the purine bases are attached to a deoxyribose sugar with a glycosidic bond.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The purine bases on DNA and RNA nucleotides are synthesized in a twelve-step reaction mechanism present in most single-celled organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Higher eukaryotes employ a similar reaction mechanism in ten reaction steps.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Purine bases are synthesized by converting phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate (PRPP) to inosine monophosphate (IMP), which is the first key intermediate in purine base biosynthesis.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Further enzymatic modification of IMP produces the adenosine and guanosine bases of nucleotides.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] GAR synthetase performs the condensation of activated glycine onto PRPP, forming glycineamide ribonucleotide (GAR).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] GAR transformylase adds a formyl group onto the amino group of GAR, forming formylglycinamide ribonucleotide (FGAR).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] FGAR amidotransferase catalyzes the addition of a nitrogen group to FGAR, forming formylglycinamidine ribonucleotide (FGAM).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] FGAM cyclase catalyzes ring closure, which involves removal of a water molecule, forming the 5-membered imidazole ring 5-aminoimidazole ribonucleotide (AIR).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] N5-CAIR synthetase transfers a carboxyl group, forming the intermediate N5-carboxyaminoimidazole ribonucleotide (N5-CAIR).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] N5-CAIR mutase rearranges the carboxyl functional group and transfers it onto the imidazole ring, forming carboxyamino- imidazole ribonucleotide (CAIR).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The two step mechanism of CAIR formation from AIR is mostly found in single celled organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Higher eukaryotes contain the enzyme AIR carboxylase, which transfers a carboxyl group directly to AIR imidazole ring, forming CAIR.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] SAICAR synthetase forms a peptide bond between aspartate and the added carboxyl group of the imidazole ring, forming N-succinyl-5-aminoimidazole-4-carboxamide ribonucleotide (SAICAR).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] SAICAR lyase removes the carbon skeleton of the added aspartate, leaving the amino group and forming 5-aminoimidazole-4-carboxamide ribonucleotide (AICAR).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] AICAR transformylase transfers a carbonyl group to AICAR, forming N-formylaminoimidazole- 4-carboxamide ribonucleotide (FAICAR).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The final step involves the enzyme IMP synthase, which performs the purine ring closure and forms the inosine monophosphate intermediate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Other DNA and RNA nucleotide bases that are linked to the ribose sugar via a glycosidic bond are thymine, cytosine and uracil (which is only found in RNA).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Uridine monophosphate biosynthesis involves an enzyme that is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and multifunctional enzymes that are located in the cytosol.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Aspartate carbamoyltransferase condenses carbamoyl phosphate with aspartate to form uridosuccinate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Dihydroorotase performs ring closure, a reaction that loses water, to form dihydroorotate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Dihydroorotate dehydrogenase, located within the mitochondrial inner membrane, oxidizes dihydroorotate to orotate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Orotate phosphoribosyl hydrolase (OMP pyrophosphorylase) condenses orotate with PRPP to form orotidine-5'-phosphate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] OMP decarboxylase catalyzes the conversion of orotidine-5'-phosphate to UMP.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] After the uridine nucleotide base is synthesized, the other bases, cytosine and thymine are synthesized.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Cytosine biosynthesis is a two-step reaction which involves the conversion of UMP to UTP.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Phosphate addition to UMP is catalyzed by a kinase enzyme.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The enzyme CTP synthase catalyzes the next reaction step: the conversion of UTP to CTP by transferring an amino group from glutamine to uridine; this forms the cytosine base of CTP.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Cytosine is a nucleotide that is present in both DNA and RNA.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Therefore, after UTP is synthesized, it must be converted into a deoxy form to be incorporated into DNA.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This conversion involves the enzyme ribonucleoside triphosphate reductase.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This reaction that removes the 2'-OH of the ribose sugar to generate deoxyribose is not affected by the bases attached to the sugar.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This non-specificity allows ribonucleoside triphosphate reductase to convert all nucleotide triphosphates to deoxyribonucleotide by a similar mechanism.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In contrast to uracil, thymine bases are found mostly in DNA, not RNA.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Cells do not normally contain thymine bases that are linked to ribose sugars in RNA, thus indicating that cells only synthesize deoxyribose-linked thymine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The enzyme thymidylate synthetase is responsible for synthesizing thymine residues from dUMP to dTMP.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This reaction transfers a methyl group onto the uracil base of dUMP to generate dTMP.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The thymidylate synthase reaction, dUMP + 5,10-methylenetetrahydrofolate ⇔ dTMP + dihydrofolate, is shown to the right.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Although there are differences between eukaryotic and prokaryotic DNA synthesis, the following section denotes key characteristics of DNA replication shared by both organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] DNA is composed of nucleotides that are joined by phosphodiester bonds.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] DNA synthesis, which takes place in the nucleus, is a semiconservative process, which means that the resulting DNA molecule contains an original strand from the parent structure and a new strand.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] DNA synthesis is catalyzed by a family of DNA polymerases that require four deoxynucleoside triphosphates, a template strand, and a primer with a free 3'OH in which to incorporate nucleotides.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In order for DNA replication to occur, a replication fork is created by enzymes called helicases which unwind the DNA helix.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Topoisomerases at the replication fork remove supercoils caused by DNA unwinding, and single-stranded DNA binding proteins maintain the two single-stranded DNA templates stabilized prior to replication.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] DNA synthesis is initiated by the RNA polymerase primase, which makes an RNA primer with a free 3'OH.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This primer is attached to the single-stranded DNA template, and DNA polymerase elongates the chain by incorporating nucleotides; DNA polymerase also proofreads the newly synthesized DNA strand.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Two types of strands are created simultaneously during replication: the leading strand, which is synthesized continuously and grows towards the replication fork, and the lagging strand, which is made discontinuously in Okazaki fragments and grows away from the replication fork.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Okazaki fragments are covalently joined by DNA ligase to form a continuous strand.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Then, to complete DNA replication, RNA primers are removed, and the resulting gaps are replaced with DNA and joined via DNA ligase.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] A protein is a polymer that is composed from amino acids that are linked by peptide bonds.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] There are more than 300 amino acids found in nature of which only twenty two, known as the proteinogenic amino acids, are the building blocks for protein.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Only green plants and most microbes are able to synthesize all of the 20 standard amino acids that are needed by all living species.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Mammals can only synthesize ten of the twenty standard amino acids.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The other amino acids, valine, methionine, leucine, isoleucine, phenylalanine, lysine, threonine and tryptophan for adults and histidine, and arginine for babies are obtained through diet.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The general structure of the standard amino acids includes a primary amino group, a carboxyl group and the functional group attached to the α-carbon.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The different amino acids are identified by the functional group.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] As a result of the three different groups attached to the α-carbon, amino acids are asymmetrical molecules.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] For all standard amino acids, except glycine, the α-carbon is a chiral center.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In the case of glycine, the α-carbon has two hydrogen atoms, thus adding symmetry to this molecule.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] With the exception of proline, all of the amino acids found in life have the L-isoform conformation.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Proline has a functional group on the α-carbon that forms a ring with the amino group.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] One major step in amino acid biosynthesis involves incorporating a nitrogen group onto the α-carbon.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In cells, there are two major pathways of incorporating nitrogen groups.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] One pathway involves the enzyme glutamine oxoglutarate aminotransferase (GOGAT) which removes the amide amino group of glutamine and transfers it onto 2-oxoglutarate, producing two glutamate molecules.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In this catalysis reaction, glutamine serves as the nitrogen source.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] An image illustrating this reaction is found to the right.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The other pathway for incorporating nitrogen onto the α-carbon of amino acids involves the enzyme glutamate dehydrogenase (GDH).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] GDH is able to transfer ammonia onto 2-oxoglutarate and form glutamate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Furthermore, the enzyme glutamine synthetase (GS) is able to transfer ammonia onto glutamate and synthesize glutamine, replenishing glutamine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The glutamate family of amino acids includes the amino acids that derive from the amino acid glutamate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This family includes: glutamate, glutamine, proline, and arginine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This family also includes the amino acid lysine, which is derived from α-ketoglutarate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The biosynthesis of glutamate and glutamine is a key step in the nitrogen assimilation discussed above.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The enzymes GOGAT and GDH catalyze the nitrogen assimilation reactions.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In bacteria, the enzyme glutamate 5-kinase initiates the biosynthesis of proline by transferring a phosphate group from ATP onto glutamate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The next reaction is catalyzed by the enzyme pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthase (P5CS), which catalyzes the reduction of the ϒ-carboxyl group of L-glutamate 5-phosphate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This results in the formation of glutamate semialdehyde, which spontaneously cyclizes to pyrroline-5-carboxylate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Pyrroline-5-carboxylate is further reduced by the enzyme pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase (P5CR) to yield a proline amino acid.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In the first step of arginine biosynthesis in bacteria, glutamate is acetylated by transferring the acetyl group from acetyl-CoA at the N-α position; this prevents spontaneous cyclization.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The enzyme N-acetylglutamate synthase (glutamate N-acetyltransferase) is responsible for catalyzing the acetylation step.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Subsequent steps are catalyzed by the enzymes N-acetylglutamate kinase, N-acetyl-gamma-glutamyl-phosphate reductase, and acetylornithine/succinyldiamino pimelate aminotransferase and yield the N-acetyl-L-ornithine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The acetyl group of acetylornithine is removed by the enzyme acetylornithinase (AO) or ornithine acetyltransferase (OAT), and this yields ornithine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Then, the enzymes citrulline and argininosuccinate convert ornithine to arginine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] There are two distinct lysine biosynthetic pathways: the diaminopimelic acid pathway and the α-aminoadipate pathway.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Aspartate semialdehyde dehydrogenase catalyzes the NADPH-dependent reduction of aspartyl phosphate to yield aspartate semialdehyde.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] 4-hydroxy-tetrahydrodipicolinate synthase adds a pyruvate group to the β-aspartyl-4-semialdehyde, and a water molecule is removed.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This causes cyclization and gives rise to (2S,4S)-4-hydroxy-2,3,4,5-tetrahydrodipicolinate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] 4-hydroxy-tetrahydrodipicolinate reductase catalyzes the reduction of (2S,4S)-4-hydroxy-2,3,4,5-tetrahydrodipicolinate by NADPH to yield Δ'-piperideine-2,6-dicarboxylate (2,3,4,5-tetrahydrodipicolinate) and H2O.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Tetrahydrodipicolinate acyltransferase catalyzes the acetylation reaction that results in ring opening and yields N-acetyl α-amino-ε-ketopimelate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] N-succinyl-α-amino-ε-ketopimelate-glutamate aminotransaminase catalyzes the transamination reaction that removes the keto group of N-acetyl α-amino-ε-ketopimelate and replaces it with an amino group to yield N-succinyl-L-diaminopimelate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] N-acyldiaminopimelate deacylase catalyzes the deacylation of N-succinyl-L-diaminopimelate to yield L,L-diaminopimelate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] DAP epimerase catalyzes the conversion of L,L-diaminopimelate to the meso form of L,L-diaminopimelate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] DAP decarboxylase catalyzes the removal of the carboxyl group, yielding L-lysine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The serine family of amino acid includes: serine, cysteine, and glycine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Most microorganisms and plants obtain the sulfur for synthesizing methionine from the amino acid cysteine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Furthermore, the conversion of serine to glycine provides the carbons needed for the biosynthesis of the methionine and histidine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] During serine biosynthesis, the enzyme phosphoglycerate dehydrogenase catalyzes the initial reaction that oxidizes 3-phospho-D-glycerate to yield 3-phosphonooxypyruvate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The following reaction is catalyzed by the enzyme phosphoserine aminotransferase, which transfers an amino group from glutamate onto 3-phosphonooxypyruvate to yield L-phosphoserine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The final step is catalyzed by the enzyme phosphoserine phosphatase, which dephosphorylates L-phosphoserine to yield L-serine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] There are two known pathways for the biosynthesis of glycine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Organisms that use ethanol and acetate as the major carbon source utilize the glyconeogenic pathway to synthesize glycine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The other pathway of glycine biosynthesis is known as the glycolytic pathway.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This pathway converts serine synthesized from the intermediates of glycolysis to glycine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In the glycolytic pathway, the enzyme serine hydroxymethyltransferase catalyzes the cleavage of serine to yield glycine and transfers the cleaved carbon group of serine onto tetrahydrofolate, forming 5,10-methylene-tetrahydrofolate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Cysteine biosynthesis is a two-step reaction that involves the incorporation of inorganic sulfur.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In microorganisms and plants, the enzyme serine acetyltransferase catalyzes the transfer of acetyl group from acetyl-CoA onto L-serine to yield O-acetyl-L-serine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The following reaction step, catalyzed by the enzyme O-acetyl serine (thiol) lyase, replaces the acetyl group of O-acetyl-L-serine with sulfide to yield cysteine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The aspartate family of amino acids includes: threonine, lysine, methionine, isoleucine, and aspartate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Lysine and isoleucine are considered part of the aspartate family even though part of their carbon skeleton is derived from pyruvate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In the case of methionine, the methyl carbon is derived from serine and the sulfur group, but in most organisms, it is derived from cysteine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The biosynthesis of aspartate is a one step reaction that is catalyzed by a single enzyme.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The enzyme aspartate aminotransferase catalyzes the transfer of an amino group from aspartate onto α-ketoglutarate to yield glutamate and oxaloacetate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Asparagine is synthesized by an ATP-dependent addition of an amino group onto aspartate; asparagine synthetase catalyzes the addition of nitrogen from glutamine or soluble ammonia to aspartate to yield asparagine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The diaminopimelic acid biosynthetic pathway of lysine belongs to the aspartate family of amino acids.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This pathway involves nine enzyme-catalyzed reactions that convert aspartate to lysine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Aspartate-semialdehyde dehydrogenase catalyzes the reduction reaction by dephosphorylation of aspartyl-β-phosphate to yield aspartate-β-semialdehyde.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Dihydrodipicolinate synthase catalyzes the condensation reaction of aspartate-β-semialdehyde with pyruvate to yield dihydrodipicolinic acid.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] 4-hydroxy-tetrahydrodipicolinate reductase catalyzes the reduction of dihydrodipicolinic acid to yield tetrahydrodipicolinic acid.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Tetrahydrodipicolinate N-succinyltransferase catalyzes the transfer of a succinyl group from succinyl-CoA on to tetrahydrodipicolinic acid to yield N-succinyl-L-2,6-diaminoheptanedioate.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] N-succinyldiaminopimelate aminotransferase catalyzes the transfer of an amino group from glutamate onto N-succinyl-L-2,6-diaminoheptanedioate to yield N-succinyl-L,L-diaminopimelic acid.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Succinyl-diaminopimelate desuccinylase catalyzes the removal of acyl group from N-succinyl-L,L-diaminopimelic acid to yield L,L-diaminopimelic acid.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Diaminopimelate epimerase catalyzes the inversion of the α-carbon of L,L-diaminopimelic acid to yield meso-diaminopimelic acid.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Siaminopimelate decarboxylase catalyzes the final step in lysine biosynthesis that removes the carbon dioxide group from meso-diaminopimelic acid to yield L-lysine.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Protein synthesis occurs via a process called translation.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] During translation, genetic material called mRNA is read by ribosomes to generate a protein polypeptide chain.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This process requires transfer RNA (tRNA) which serves as an adaptor by binding amino acids on one end and interacting with mRNA at the other end; the latter pairing between the tRNA and mRNA ensures that the correct amino acid is added to the chain.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Protein synthesis occurs in three phases: initiation, elongation, and termination.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Prokaryotic (archaeal and bacterial) translation differs from eukaryotic translation; however, this section will mostly focus on the commonalities between the two organisms.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Before translation can begin, the process of binding a specific amino acid to its corresponding tRNA must occur.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This reaction, called tRNA charging, is catalyzed by aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] A specific tRNA synthetase is responsible for recognizing and charging a particular amino acid.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Furthermore, this enzyme has special discriminator regions to ensure the correct binding between tRNA and its cognate amino acid.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This is followed by the transfer of the aminoacyl group from aminoacyl-AMP to a tRNA molecule.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The combination of these two steps, both of which are catalyzed by aminoacyl tRNA synthetase, produces a charged tRNA that is ready to add amino acids to the growing polypeptide chain.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In addition to binding an amino acid, tRNA has a three nucleotide unit called an anticodon that base pairs with specific nucleotide triplets on the mRNA called codons; codons encode a specific amino acid.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] This interaction is possible thanks to the ribosome, which serves as the site for protein synthesis.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The ribosome possesses three tRNA binding sites: the aminoacyl site (A site), the peptidyl site (P site), and the exit site (E site).
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] There are numerous codons within an mRNA transcript, and it is very common for an amino acid to be specified by more than one codon; this phenomenon is called degeneracy.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] In all, there are 64 codons, 61 of each code for one of the 20 amino acids, while the remaining codons specify chain termination.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] As previously mentioned, translation occurs in three phases: initiation, elongation, and termination.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Following initiation, the polypeptide chain is extended via anticodon:codon interactions, with the ribosome adding amino acids to the polypeptide chain one at a time.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Translocation "kicks off" the tRNA at the E site and shifts the tRNA from the A site into the P site, leaving the A site free for an incoming tRNA to add another amino acid.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] The last stage of translation occurs when a stop codon enters the A site.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Errors in biosynthetic pathways can have deleterious consequences including the malformation of macromolecules or the underproduction of functional molecules.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/biosynthesis] Below are examples that illustrate the disruptions that occur due to these inefficiencies.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/deltaproteobacteria] The **Myxococcota** are a phylum of bacteria known as the fruiting gliding bacteria.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/deltaproteobacteria] All species of this group are Gram-negative.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/deltaproteobacteria] They are predominantly aerobic genera that release myxospores in unfavorable environments.
[src:acidulidesulfobacteriota/deltaproteobacteria] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
